occurrences.line_text: Am th'only daughter of a King and Queene,
Of Gloriane great Queene of glory bright,
And at her parting said, She Queene of Faeries hight.
O happy Queene of Faeries, that hast found
Of that great Queene may well gaine worthy grace:
In which that fairest Faerie Queene doth dwell,
Twixt that great faery Queene and Paynim king,
Forth came that auncient Lord and aged Queene,
Did seeme such, as she was, a goodly maiden Queene.
That godly King and Queene did passionate,
Backe to returne to that great Faerie Queene,
Vnto his Farie Queene backe to returne:
To serue againe his soueraine Elfin Queene,
Fresh memory in me of that great Queene,
Great and most glorious virgin Queene aliue,
To seeke her game: Or as that famous Queene
She is the mighty Queene of Faerie,
To serue that Queene with all my powre and might.
Thy name, Ã´ soueraine Queene, to blazon farre away.
Thy name Ã´ soueraine Queene, thy realme and race,
There Alma like a virgin Queene most bright,
Vnto his Faerie Queene he might present:
O soueraigne Queene, whose prayse I would endite,
Which long'd to Angela, the Saxon Queene,
As thee, ï¿½ Queene, the matter of my song,
His Faery Queene, for whom he did complaine:
Or that his Faery Queene were such, as shee:
Yet there that cruell Queene auengeresse,
But to that sacred Saint my soueraigne Queene,
The Queene of loue, & Prince of peace fro[m] heauen blest.
For Chian folke to pourtraict beauties Queene,
And to the Queene of beautie close did call,
The Queene of beautie, and of loue the mother,
Great Venus, Queene of beautie and of grace,
Great God of men and women, queene of th'ayre,
And by his side his Queene with coronall,
Did to the Faery Queene her way addresse,
That soueraine Queene, that mightie Emperesse,
The semblant of this false by his faire beauties Queene.
And Queene of Amazons, in armes well tride,
Ere long their Queene her selfe, halfe like a man
That she a Queene, and come of Princely kynd,
Vnto her Queene, his freedome to haue gayned;
Doe serue a Queene, that not far hence doth wone,
That is a mayden Queene of high renowne,
To haue bene done against her Lady Queene,
There shall ye see my souerayne Lady Queene
And foule blaspheme that Queene for forged guyle,
Vnto the presence of that gratious Queene:
But false Duessa now vntitled Queene,
And to their Queene for iudgement loudly call,
And humbly gan that mightie Queene entreat,
Then taking humble leaue of that great Queene,
Vnto his soueraine Queene her suite for to commend.
As in your selfe, O soueraine Lady Queene,
The widow Queene my mother, which then hight
Which by the Faery Queene was on him layd,
Whether it were the traine of beauties Queene,
The which the Faery Queene had long afore
Of ancient Kings and Queenes, that had of yore
Whereon the Faery Queenes pourtract was writ,
As the proud Persian Queenes accustomed:
Kings Queenes, Lords Ladies, Knights & Damzels gent
With such queint vsage, fit for Queenes and Kings,
And kindling new his courage seeming queint,
With thousand spots of colours queint elect,
Nor hart could wish for any queint deuice,
Magnificke Virgin, that in queint disguise
With such queint vsage, fit for Queenes and Kings,
Stuft with steele-headed darts, wherewith she queld
That cursed weapon, when his cruell foes he queld.
Eftsoones their stubborne courages were queld,
At sight thereof she was with terror queld,
And their faint harts with senselesse horrour queld,
Her ready to assaile, was greatly queld,
Was with his ghastly count'nance nothing queld,
With hearts dismay and inward dolour queld,
Is forcibly kept downe, till he be throughly queld.
Such ioy he had, their stubborne harts to quell,
Each other bent his enimy to quell,
Yet so extremely did the buffe him quell,
They heapt huge strokes, the scorned life to quell,
Whose father Hercules in Fraunce did quell,
Sith dint of steele his carcas could not quell:
And Artegall doth quell.
But him likewise with that same speare he eke did quell.
Much did his words the gentle Ladie quell,
From that sad land, where he his syre did quell,
Whence ere he could recou'r, he did him quell,
How could the death dare euer her to quell?
That monstrous Beast by finall force to quell,
Well prou'd in that same day, when Ioue those Gyants quelled.
And quench the flame of furious despight,
The which doth quench the brond of hellish smart,
The sparks soone quench, the springing seed outweed,
Nath'lesse now quench thy whot emboyling wrath:
Therein did often quench his thristy heat,
So easie was to quench his flamed mind
And quench the brond of his conceiued ire.
Yet nought can quench mine inly flaming syde,
To seeke young men, to quench her flaming thurst,
To quench the flames, which she had tyn'd before,
In generation seeke to quench their inward fire.
Offred him drinke, to quench his thirstie heat,
So for to quench his fire, he did it more augment.
Their feruent appetites they quenched had,
Where it should not be quenched day nor night,
She broke his wanton darts, and quenched base desire.
Fraile harts, yet quenched not; like starry light
In whose faire eyes, like lamps of quenched fire,
And quenched quite, like a consumed torch,
And quenched is with Cupids greater flame:
Out quenched, leaues no skill nor difference of wight.
To kindle his quencht fire, and thousand causes wrought.
Ne can be quencht, within my secret bowels bee.
And hauing quencht her burning fier brands,
Out of the flames, which he had quencht whylere
This fire be quencht by any wit or might,
Her well beseemes that Quest (quoth Satyrane)
To weet, what wight he was, and what his quest:
But to the rest, which in this Quest proceed
Vpon an hard aduenture yet in quest,
Resolued to pursue his former quest;
Irenaes quest pursewed,
To follow his old quest, the which him forth did call.
Had him misfalne in his aduenturous quest;
Nor hold from suite of his auowed quest,
On his first quest, the which him forth did call,
Sir Artegall return'd from his late quest,
Atchieu'd so hard a quest, as few before;
What is that quest (quoth then Sir Artegall)
And then to his first quest he passed forth along.
To follow his first quest, when as he spyde
To haue thy presence in my present quest,
Did sleepe all night through weary trauell of his quest.
So as he was pursuing of his quest
On his first quest, in which did him betide
In that same quest which Fortune on him cast,
If he for slouth forslackt so famous quest.
Although his quest were farre afore him gon;
His former quest, so full of toile and paine;
Another quest, another game in vew
This gentle knight, from sewing his first quest,
Of his first quest, which he had long forlore;
He went forth on his quest, and did, that him befell.
But first was question made, which of those Knights
Who staying nought to question from aloofe,
But not for those she now in question came,
And then to question of her present woe;
And gan to question streight how she it knew.
The man awoke, and would haue questiond more;
Though also those mote question'd be aright,
Mongst which Cymochles of her questioned,
Till he had questioned the cause of their dissent.
Mongst which the theeues them questioned againe,
That once he could not moue, nor quich at all;
With windy Nitre and quick Sulphur fraught,
Yet wondrous quick and persant was his spright,
Quick, the first authour of all Elfin kind:
More busying his quicke eyes, her face to view,
Of death and labour lay, halfe dead, halfe quicke,
That nought mote hinder his quicke preiudize:
And in their entrails, full of quicke Brimston,
That bitter stownd, but turning quicke aside
And a quicke mouing Spirit did arret
Those feeling wordes so neare the quicke did goe,
The royall child with readie quicke foresight,
But Calidore, that was more quicke of sight,
Leaue faytor quickely that misgotten weft
Sternely did bid him quickely thence auaunt,
Goe caytiue Elfe, him quickly ouertake,
But he her quickly reared vp againe:
But him the Squire made quickly to retrate,
The light-foot Squire her quickly turnd around,
To throw his rider: who can quickly ryse
And zealous hast away is quickly gone
They bene ybrought; he quickly does him dight,
Forth launched quickly, as she did desire,
He graunted: then the Faery quickly raught
Betwixt her feeble armes her quickly keight,
For him likewise he quickly downe did smight,
But he her quickly stayd, and forst to wend withall.
Whom hauing quickly arm'd againe anew,
Goe damzell quickly, doe thy selfe addresse,
But quickly she it ouerpast, so soone
She quickly caught her sword, & shield about her bound.
That quickned the dull spright with musicall comfort.
Doe life conceiue and quickned are by kynd:
And quickning faith, that earst was woxen weake,
But by the way, there is a great Quicksand,
That quicksand nigh with water couered;
It called was the quicksand of Vnthriftyhed.
Might there be heard: but carelesse Quiet lyes,
And layes the soule to sleepe in quiet graue?
For we be come vnto a quiet rode,
And ended all her woe in quiet death.
She them besought, during their quiet treague,
Then gan a cursed hand the quiet wombe
That once their quiet gouernment annoyd,
Whose countreis he redus'd to quiet state,
Out of her quiet slomber did awake,
Her teme at her commaundement quiet stands,
And to the Castle gate approcht in quiet wise.
Out of his quiet slomber him abrade,
In stead thereof sweet peace and quiet age
Where they might hide their heads in quiet rest,
The bellowes noyse disturb'd his quiet rest,
On him, the which his quiet slomber brake:
That did her passed paines in quiet rest assoyle.
And to afflicted minds sweet rest and quiet sends.
Warn'd man and beast in quiet rest be shrowded,
And troubled had their quiet loues delight.
Ne once my minds vnmoued quiet grieue,
This lowly quiet life, which I inherite here.
And in this quiet make you safer liue.
And all things quieted, the Elfin Knight
By them the Sprite doth passe in quietly,
And suffered them to passen quietly:
And quietly doth hold it in his hand,
But ioyous peace and quietnesse alway,
That weaker sence it could haue rauisht quight:
Whiles you in carelesse sleepe are drowned quight.
That all my senses were bereaued quight:
From hope of heauen hath thee excluded quight,
And him to dust thought to haue battred quight,
Their kingdome spoild, and countrey wasted quight:
and strips Duessa quight.
And whiles he stroue his combred clubbe to quight
It dimmes the dazed eyen, and daunts the senses quight.
And her foundation forst, and feebled quight,
Thus when they had the witch disrobed quight,
O holy Sire (quoth he) how shall I quight
He thought attonce him to haue swallowd quight,
And with her wondrous beautie rauisht quight,
And from the head the body sundred quight.
And him in bloud and durt deformed quight.
Where finding life not yet dislodged quight,
Againe through both the sides he strooke him quight,
Sometimes the one would lift the other quight
It she reduced, but himselfe destroyed quight.
With which her soueraigne mercy thou doest quight?
To see so faire things mard, and spoyled quight:
Least his fraile senses were emperisht quight,
Was of his forward hope deceiued quight;
Out of the goodly heauen amoued quight,
The heardes out of their foldes were loosed quight,
He was so wasted and forpined quight,
Is woxen so deform'd, that he has quight
Of her dew honour was despoyled quight,
But she faire Lady ouercommen quight
Into his throate and life it pierced quight,
And ouerbore beyond his crouper quight,
And of the wicked world forgotten quight,
Through wilfull penury consumed quight,
And fire deuoure the ayre, and hell them quight,
Slew cruelly, and in the riuer drowned quight.
Gan fade, and liuely spirits deaded quight:
As all things else in time are chaunged quight.
Does race her castle quight.
High God, whose goodnesse he despaired quight,
And former liuelod fayle, she left me quight,
Rather then see her people spoiled quight,
And caused him to be disarmed quight,
Thought with his speare him quight haue ouerwent.
Defeated had the other faytour quight,
By her beguyled, and confounded quight:
That seem'd their soules they wold haue ryuen quight
As he to peeces would haue chopt it quight:
Hath pruned from the natiue tree, and cropped quight.
Whom now her keepers had forsaken quight,
She was by him aduiz'd, to send me quight
As if he would haue passed through him quight:
His dearest ioynt he sure had broken quight.
Of that displeasure, broke his bag-pipe quight,
Yet Calidore did not despise him quight,
And saw his shepheards cottage spoyled quight,
Argument worthy of Moeonian quill,
Presume so high to stretch mine humble quill?
And fethered with an vnlucky quill;
Th'embroderd quilt she lightly vp did lift,
On his horse necke before the quilted sell,
And quilted vppon sattin white as milke,
But in a Iacket quilted richly rare,
The more he laughes, and does her closely quip,
And all the quire of birds did sweetly sing,
He ceast, and then gan all the quire of birdes
Of all, which there was doing in that quire:
That I his shield haue quit from dying foe.
Can now deuise to quit a thrall from such a plight?
Which quit from death yet quakes in euery lim
Till from her cursed foe thou haue her freely quit.
Quit from that daunger, forth their course they kept,
Can wretched Lady, quit from wofull state,
They left behind them, glad to be so quit:
Glad to be quit from that proud Tyrants awe,
And quite dismembred hath: the thirstie land
Much feared I to haue bene quite abhord,
Through vainely crossed shield he quite did pierce,
That from his saddle quite he did him beare:
Was quite dismembred, and his members chast
This Nymph, quite tyr'd with heat of scorching ayre,
Thenceforth me desolate he quite forsooke,
But with that percing noise flew open quite, or brast.
And smote off quite his right leg by the knee,
Was vanisht quite, and of that monstrous mas
How shall I quite the paines, ye suffer for my sake?
And what I cannot quite, requite with vsuree.
To driue him to despaire, and quite to quaile,
And double quite, for that he on them spent,
And this bright Angels towre quite dims that towre of glas.
Through passing brightnesse, which did quite co[n]found
Snatcht vp both horse & man, to beare them quite away.
And quite a sunder broke. Forth flowed fresh
Quite through his shield, and in his shoulder seasd,
Of his huge taile he quite a sunder cleft,
And made such way, that hewd it quite in twaine;
And fairly quite him of th'imputed blame,
Welling out streames of teares, and quite dismayd
And quite contrary to her sisters kind;
That quite bereau'd the rash beholders sight:
Full fast away, and did her quite forsake;
And furious fits at earst quite weren quaild:
That all his left side it did quite disarme;
And him dishabled quite. But he was wise
Deepe in their flesh, quite through the yron walles,
That quite it cloue his plumed crest in tway,
His painted nimble wings, and vanisht quite away.
Which hewing quite a sunder, further way
That quite disparted all the linked frame,
Quite through his braine. He tombling downe on ground,
Doth blow them quite away, and in the Ocean cast.
It was auoided quite, and throwne out priuily.
That quite his hart from Guendolene remou'd,
At last quite rauisht with delight, to heare
That how the time was fled, they quite forgate,
Ere long they rowed were quite out of sight,
Vntill he quite had spent his perlous store,
She turnd her bote about, and from them rowed quite.
But this same was to that quite contrary,
Quite molten into lust and pleasure lewd;
Auoided quite, she gan her selfe despoile,
She soundly slept, & carefull thoughts did quite assoile.
That in short space their foes they haue quite terrifide.
And quite from of th'earth their memory be rast?
That through his threesquare scuchin percing quite,
So weening to haue arm'd him, she did quite disarme.
And through the linked mayles empierced quite,
It left, but both did quite drye vp, and blast;
All couerd with thick woods, that quite it ouercame.
Or quite deuourd her beauties scornefull grace.
And the rich furrowes flote, all quite fordonne:
Quite of all hope, wherewith he long had fed
And without reskew led her quite away.
And all her senses with abashment quite were quayld.
In her fraile wit, that now her quite forlore:
With extreme fury he became quite mad,
And breaking quite his gyrlond euer greene,
Quite through transfixed with a deadly dart,
She found, and all their glory quite decayd,
And quenched quite, like a consumed torch,
Was vanisht quite, as it were not the same,
So seemd those two, as growne together quite,
Conueyed quite away to liuing wight vnknowen.
And that great golden chaine quite to diuide,
Quite ouerblowne, yet doth not passe so cleare,
Whom to thy selfe thou takest quite away?
That famous moniment hath quite defaste,
Are quite deuourd, and brought to nought by little bits?
Pierst through his beuer quite into his brow,
That from his shoulders quite his head he reft:
Are washt away quite from their memorie.
And hearts quite robbed with so glorious sight,
That horse and man to ground he quite did beare,
And rend a sunder quite, if he thereto list striue.
That quite it chynd his backe behind the sell,
From one to other so quite contrary:
And through the forrest bore her quite away,
And now he her quite ouertaken had;
Hauing his carrion corse quite sencelesse left,
And others quite excluded forth, did ly
Would quite haue burst through great abundance of her smart.
Me seemes the world is runne quite out of square,
That they haue crusht the Crab, and quite him borne
That makes me feare in time he will vs quite forsake.
And lastly all that Castle quite he raced,
And each estate quite out of order go'th?
And chaced quite out of the field, that none
That all his ribs he quite in peeces broke,
That he him maymed quite, and all his shoulder split.
And plucked quite from all possessors hand,
That to the ground him quite she ouerthrew,
Halfe of her shield he shared quite away,
And bore him quite out of his saddle, longer
They quite forgot, and scornd all former law;
Quite topside turuey, and the pagan hound
That quite smit off his arme, as he it vp did lift.
And lighting on his horses head, him quite did mall.
He had him surely clouen quite in twaine.
And with his mortal steel quite throgh the body strooke.
But when he could not quite it, with one stripe
The vse of armes, and battell quite forgone:
And forced him to throw it quite away,
By open force to fetch her quite away:
So bore her quite away, nor well nor ill apayd.
Into the sea he droue quite from that soyle,
Him charge with guilt, but rather doe quite clame:
He quite forsooke, and fled himselfe away for feare.
Quite ouerthrow, who now ginnes to despize
Beare off their blowes, from percing thorough quite.
That quite they seem'd past helpe of surgery,
By this quite slaine in so vnequall fight:
That all his launce in peeces shiuered quite,
Her selfe quite through the bodie doth engore,
When all his strokes he saw auoyded quite,
That whether quite from them for to retrate
But quite are dimmed, when she is in place.
His hart quite deaded was with anguish great,
Yet left not quite, but drew a litle space
Who faire him quited, as that courteous was:
Who faire them quites, as him beseemed best,
Quites Mirabell from dreed:
Then since that strange Knights loue from him was quitted,
And at her backe a bow and quiuer gay,
Her bow and gilden quiuer lying him beside.
Her bow and painted quiuer, had vnlaste
But still did lie as dead, and quake, and quiuer,
That like an hazell wand, it quiuered and quooke.
The quiuering steele his aymed end well knew,
Such as the Indians in their quiuers hide;
With that at him a quiu'ring dart he threw,
That euery member of his bodie quooke.
And tottred like two towres, which through a tempest quooke.
That like an hazell wand, it quiuered and quooke.
Be well aware, quoth then that Ladie milde,
Yea but (quoth she) the perill of this place
Therefore I read beware. Fly fly (quoth then
Ah my deare Sonne (quoth he) how should, alas,
Far hence (quoth he) in wastfull wildernesse
(Quoth then that aged man;) the way to win
Hither (quoth he) me Archimago sent,
Why Dame (quoth he) what hath ye thus dismayd?
Curse on that Crosse (quoth then the Sarazin)
Then groning deepe, Nor damned Ghost, (quoth he,)
Quoth then the knight, by whose mischieuous arts
We may not chaunge (quoth he) this euil plight,
Quoth she, his princely puissance doth abate,
Ah dearest Dame, (quoth then the Paynim bold,)
Oft tempred is (quoth she) with muchell smart:
O but I feare the fickle freakes (quoth shee)
Why dame (quoth he) what oddes can euer bee,
Yea but (quoth she) he beares a charmed shield,
(Quoth she) how euer now in garments gilt,
Ah Dame (quoth he) thou temptest me in vaine,
Not so (quoth she) but sith that heauens king
Aye me, Deare dame (quoth he) well may I rew
Ah dearest Lord (quoth she) how might that bee,
Ah dearest dame (quoth he) how might I see
Not far away (quoth he) he hence doth wonne
Tell on (quoth she) the wofull Tragedie,
Ah Ladie deare, quoth then the gentle knight,
O but (quoth she) great griefe will not be tould,
Right so; (quoth he) but he, that neuer would,
But griefe (quoth she) does greater grow displaid,
Despaire breedes not (quoth he) where faith is staid.
No faith so fast (quoth she) but flesh does paire.
Flesh may empaire (quoth he) but reason can repaire.
To do her dye (quoth Vna) were despight,
Full hard it is (quoth he) to read aright
Ah curteous knight (quoth she) what secret wound
Deare Dame (quoth he) you sleeping sparkes awake,
And am I now in safetie sure (quoth he)
Feare nought: (quoth he) no daunger now is nye?
Iwote (quoth he) whom triall late did teach,
I that hight Treuisan (quoth he) will ride
What franticke fit (quoth he) hath thus distraught
(Quoth he) knowes best the termes established;
O matrone sage (quoth she) I hither came,
Indeede (quoth she) that should her trouble sore,
What end (quoth she) should cause vs take such paine,
Faire knight (quoth he) Hierusalem that is,
Vnworthy wretch (quoth he) of so great grace,
(Quoth he) as wretched, and liu'd in like paine.
O let me not (quoth he) then turne againe
Then shall I soone, (quoth he) so God me grace,
O holy Sire (quoth he) how shall I quight
(Quoth he) the troubler of my happie peace,
None but that saw (quoth he) would weene for troth,
He liues, (quoth he) and boasteth of the fact,
But if that carelesse heauens (quoth she) despise
Palmer (quoth he) death is an equall doome
Ah wretch (quoth he) thy destinies withstand
Who so in pompe of proud estate (quoth she)
Faire Sir (quoth he) what man can shun the hap,
Phedon I hight (quoth he) and do aduaunce
My Lord (quoth he) me sent, and streight behight
Faire Sir (quoth she) be not displeasd at all;
What flames (quoth he) when I thee present see,
Indeede (quoth he) through fowle intemperaunce,
Perdy (quoth he) yet neuer eye did vew,
What secret place (quoth he) can safely hold
